quest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Auberville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Turberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, probably from Thouberville (Eure), or possibly from Trubleville (Seine-Maritime), both in France. The two may have been confused in surname usage."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Auberville II was born about 1164, in Dover, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, William d'Auberville Lord of Westenhanger, was 11162 and his mother, Maud Glanville, was 19. He had at least 1 son with Mathilda de Glanville. He died in 1200, at the age of 37."},"et":{"um 1164–1200":"umbes 1164–1200","1164–1200":"1164–1200","1168–Male":"1168–Surnud","1170–1252":"1170–1252","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1160–1201":"1160–1201","1170–1229":"1170–1229","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1146–1173":"1146–1173","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1252":"1252","1164":"1164","1130":"1130","1173":"1173","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","um 1164":"umbes 1164","1146":"1146","1201":"1201","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1229":"1229","Langdon, Dover, Kent, England":"Dover, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Iden and Isham, Sussex":"Iden, Suss